Presentatum . . . . quod Johannes Hamund de Scardeburgh et alii fuerunt consueti malefactores de venacione domini Regis 3 qui predictus Johannes venit coram Justiciariis et optulit se acquietare per [321b] sacramentum suum et triginta et sex hominum quia non inventus fuit cum manuopere per viridarios et forestarios sicut continetur in carta predicta 3 ideo consideratum est quod se acquietet modo predicto 3 qui venit et se acquietavit ut predictum est 3 ideo ipse inde quietus.

John Hamond of Scarborough and others were confirmed poachers. The first-named appears and offers to aequit himself by the oath of thirty-six men. He is permitted to do so, and does acquit himself in this manner.
